The parties involved in the Third Amended and Restated Common Terms Agreement are:

1. Sabine Pass Liquefaction, LLC, a limited liability company organized and existing under the laws of the State of Delaware (the “Borrower”);
2. Each subsidiary of the Borrower that is a party to this Agreement from time to time in accordance with the terms of this Agreement (the “Restricted Subsidiaries,” and together with the Borrower, the “Loan Parties”);
3. Each Secured Debt Holder Group Representative that is a party to this Agreement from time to time in accordance with the terms of this Agreement;
4. Each Secured Hedge Representative that is a party to this Agreement from time to time in accordance with the terms of this Agreement;
5. Each Secured Gas Hedge Representative that is a party to this Agreement from time to time in accordance with the terms of this Agreement;
6. Société Générale, as the Common Security Trustee;
7. Société Générale, as the Intercreditor Agent.

A District Default under the lease agreement occurs if the District fails to:

1. Pay Annual Rental or Additional Rent within 30 calendar days after written notice from the Landlord, provided the Landlord has fulfilled its obligations under Section 7.3;
2. Perform or observe any non-monetary obligation under the Lease within the specified period (30 days if no express period is provided), unless the failure constitutes a District Delay, and the District fails to cure the default within 30 days after written notice from the Landlord (or within 120 days if the District promptly commences and diligently pursues cure);
3. Engage in any sublease or assignment not permitted by Section 21;
4. Abandon the Premises.

It is specifically understood that failure to violate the Anti-Deficiency Acts or failure to obtain a certification of the availability of appropriated funds in accordance with Section 26.1 does not constitute a District Default. However, the Landlord may still pursue remedies for District Negligence or breach of the Lease.
